   176	### B. The spec itself (`spec/v0/`)
   177	
   178	**Phase 0 writes only `spec/README.md` and `spec/v0/README.md`.** Those
   179	READMEs describe the versioning policy and enumerate the planned
   180	chapters (with a "filled in Phase N" note beside each), but no
   181	chapter content or schema files are written at bootstrap. The
   182	conventions below apply to those later-phase writes.
   183	
   184	When chapters are eventually written (Phases 1, 2, 4, 11, 12):
   185	**normative language** (MUST / SHOULD / MAY per RFC 2119), numbered
   186	sections, explicit cross-references, and *no* references to specific
   187	technology choices. Example boundaries:
   188	
   189	- `04-task-protocol.md` (Phase 2) will define the task state machine,
   190	  the claim-token rule, the submit-idempotency rule, and the wire
   191	  format for task objects. It will **not** say "Postgres `tasks` table"
   192	  — that's a reference-impl detail. It may say "a conforming task
   193	  store MUST provide atomic claim with linearizable semantics" and
   194	  leave the mechanism to the implementor.
   195	- `05-event-protocol.md` (Phase 4) will define the event object shape,
   196	  the transactional invariant (event insert MUST be atomic with the
   197	  state change it describes), and the delivery guarantees subscribers
   198	  can rely on. Whether that's LISTEN/NOTIFY, Kafka, or a WebSocket is
   199	  out of scope.
   200	- `06-integrator.md` (Phase 4) will pin git topology invariants:
   201	  namespaces (`work/*`, `trial/*`, `main`), sole-integrator rule,
   202	  squash rule, eval-manifest shape. Applies regardless of git host.
   203	
   204	Every wire-format object will eventually have a JSON Schema under
   205	`spec/v0/schemas/` (first ones land in Phase 1). The Markdown docs
   206	link to them. CI validates schemas from Phase 1 onward and enforces
   207	reference-impl Pydantic-model parity from Phase 3 onward.
   208	
   209	### C. `reference/` at bootstrap
   210	
   211	- `reference/README.md` — "What's implemented, what's stubbed, what
   212	  spec version is targeted." At bootstrap: declares `targets:
   213	  eden-protocol/v0 (draft — chapters not yet written)` and lists all
   214	  services/packages as "empty; lands in Phase N".
   215	- Each `reference/services/*/` and `reference/packages/*/` — a
   216	  `.gitkeep` only. Root `pyproject.toml` and per-member
   217	  `pyproject.toml` files **land in Phase 3** with the first real
   218	  package (`eden-contracts`), not at bootstrap.
   219	- **No code yet.** Bootstrap is structure + section-level READMEs.
   220	  Phase 1 starts writing the spec.
   221	
   222	### D. `conformance/` at bootstrap
   223	
   224	- `conformance/README.md` only. Describes the intended shape: scenarios
   225	  drive an implementation-under-test via its advertised protocol
   226	  endpoints; assertions verify invariants. Actual suite is a later
   227	  roadmap phase once enough protocol surface is stable to test.
